<recipeml version="0.5">
  <recipe>
    <head>
      <title>Amy Nelson's Giblet Gravy</title>
      <categories>
        <cat>Holiday</cat></categories>
      <yield>2</yield></head>
    <ingredients>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>8</qty>
          <unit>cups</unit></amt>
        <item>Broth</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>4</qty>
          <unit>tablespoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Roux (8 tbsp. flour and 8 tbsp. butter, mixed) (up to 8)</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty/>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Neck; liver and gizzard (cooked), chopped</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>6</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Hard-boiled egg; chopped</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>2</qty>
          <unit>tablespoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Parsley; chopped</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>2</qty>
          <unit>tablespoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Pimento; chopped</item></ing></ingredients>
    <directions>
      <step>  Bring broth to a boil and thicken with roux. (Add more roux to desired
  gravy thickness) Remove meat from cooked neck and liver and gizzard. Chop
  meat and add to broth. Add eggs, parsley and pimento and season to taste.
  Makes about 2 quarts gravy.
  
  Recipe by: Green Pastures Restaurant
  
  Posted to TNT - Prodigy's Recipe Exchange Newsletter  by Sherry Zeiss
  &lt;zeiss@eden.com&gt; on Nov 20, 1997
 
</step></directions></recipe></recipeml>
